commentary: Mohammad Amir to Warner, 1 run first-ball drop! Put down by Azhar Ali at second slip. Particularly difficult chance. He dives full-length to his wrong side - his left - and the ball does not stick. Swing for Amir right away. Full awayswinger, starts outside off, and curls away further. Warner has a bigger swing at it. Slashes hard and sends an outside edge. Azhar dives to his left, attempts the catch with both hands, but it pops out

commentary: Junaid Khan to Warner, 1 run and there it is! A century off 78 balls. Fullish on off stump and he plays a defensive push into the off side, not too far from the finish of Junaid's follow-through, but both he and Head take off immediately to ensure they complete the quick single with ease. This is his fastest hundred in ODIs - his previous quickest was off 92 balls

commentary: Hasan Ali to Warner, 2 runs Oh dear! Warner skies one in the air, and Amir drops it. Full on the stumps, Warner aims for a leg-side mow. He can't only skew it in the air. Amir runs in from long-on, the sun squinting in his eyes, but shells it. Pops in and out. The camera pans out to coach Arthur and fielding coach Rixon in the Pakistan change room. Arthur covers his face up with his hands while Rixon shakes his head. Pakistan's fielding goof-ups continue

commentary: Junaid Khan to Warner, OUT carved away in the air. It dies in front of point, but Azam bends forward and snaps up a low catch. He claims it, and they go upstairs. It's a clean catch and a cramping David Warner walks back for 179, his best ODI score. No double-hundred for him, though. Slower short ball, cuts away from Warner. He reaches out for the ball and scythes it in the air. The opening stand ends on 284

Smith flat-bats it in the air and holes out

commentary: Cummins to Shoaib Malik, no run appeal for caught behind? Did that loop off the arm or glove behind to Smith running back and across to his right at wide slip. Skiddy short ball, leaps off the surface, angled in, Malik was probably not sure whether to duck or fend. In the end, he does a bit of both, and also takes his eyes off the ball. The ball pings his forearm and loops over to slip. Malik clutches his wrist in pain. Australia did well not to review it. The physio is out to attend to Malik

commentary: Cummins to Umar Akmal, no run short of a length and angled in, Umar jumps off the ground and fends it just beside the pitch on the leg side. Cummins runs in and across to his right, attacks the ball, picks it and aims a throw at the striker's end. Umar, who was searching for a risky single - there wasn't a single there actually - spins back and survives. Babar does not move. A direct hit could have had him

commentary: Zampa to Hasan Ali, OUT down the track comes Hasan, and Pakistan are eight down. Slowed it down, the tailender was through his slog well before it arrived, and then it spun away and offered Wade a simple stumping

commentary: Starc to Wahab Riaz, OUT and that is that. Yorker on middle stump, Wahab makes room to try and drive that through the covers, and he misses. The bails light up, to signal a 57-run win for Australia. Shoaib Malik, who retired hurt after being hit on the forearm, won't come out to resume his innings
